(
  'Invention Secrecy Act — 5,000+ Patents Under Government Gag Order Since 1951',
  'Under the Invention Secrecy Act of 1951, the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office holds over 5,000 patent applications under active secrecy orders. Inventors cannot publish, build, or sell their inventions. A 1971 restricted technology list reveals solar PV systems exceeding 20% efficiency and energy conversion systems exceeding 70–80% efficiency are subject to restriction.',
  'The Invention Secrecy Act of 1951 (35 U.S.C. §§ 181–188) authorizes the Commissioner of Patents to issue "secrecy orders" on any patent application that a government agency determines could damage national security if published. Once a secrecy order is issued, the inventor is legally prohibited from publishing the invention, building a working prototype, or licensing or selling it — under threat of criminal prosecution. The order can be renewed annually and maintained indefinitely.

Current scope (Federation of American Scientists data, 2024):
- Over 5,000 patent applications are currently under active secrecy orders
- The current list of technology categories subject to restriction has been withheld from FOIA requests — the full scope of what is classified is itself classified
- A 1971 list of restricted technology categories obtained by researcher Michael Ravnitzky through FOIA revealed that the following are subject to potential secrecy orders: solar photovoltaic generators exceeding 20% efficiency, energy conversion systems exceeding 70–80% efficiency, and other advanced power generation technologies

Historical pattern:
- Secrecy orders were first issued for nuclear weapons technology during WWII
- After WWII, the mechanism was institutionalized and expanded through the 1951 Act
- Critics note that the "national security" justification has historically been applied to energy technologies that would disrupt incumbent fossil fuel industries — though this cannot be confirmed because the current restricted categories list is itself classified
- The Patent Office does not publish statistics on which government agencies request secrecy orders for which technology categories

A February 6, 2026 interview on Tucker Carlson''s X channel brought the Invention Secrecy Act to mainstream attention, generating documented viral engagement across political audiences.',
