(
  '32 FDA Transparency Reforms — 17 Unimplemented Across Four Administrations Since 2017',
  'A March 2026 JAMA Viewpoint by CSPI identifies 32 actionable FDA transparency reforms — 17 first identified in 2017 and still unimplemented across four administrations. Key unreformed areas include the GRAS loophole, drug application refusal disclosure, and FOIA document release. All 10 surveyed measures showed bipartisan public support.',
  'The Center for Science in the Public Interest (CSPI) published a March 2026 JAMA Viewpoint identifying 32 specific, actionable FDA transparency reforms — 17 of which were first formally identified and recommended in 2017, during the first Trump administration, and remain unimplemented through the Biden administration and into the second Trump administration.

Key unreformed areas (from the JAMA Viewpoint):

1. GRAS Loophole: The Generally Recognized As Safe (GRAS) designation allows food manufacturers to self-certify that new food additives are safe without FDA review or notification. An estimated 10,000+ food additives are in commercial use without any FDA safety review. The FDA has proposed closing this loophole repeatedly; it remains open.

2. Drug Application Refusals: The FDA does not consistently publish information when it refuses or rejects a drug application (Complete Response Letters), leaving prescribers and patients unaware of the full safety or efficacy concerns that led to rejection.

3. FOIA Compliance: The FDA''s FOIA responsiveness has declined under budget constraints; CSPI documents specific categories of documents that should be routinely publicly available but require multi-year FOIA litigation.

4. Clinical Trial Reporting: Not all federally funded clinical trials report their results to ClinicalTrials.gov within the legally required 12-month window. The FDA does not consistently enforce this requirement.

Survey data: All 10 transparency measures tested in a 2022 bipartisan public survey showed majority support across both Republican and Democratic respondents — suggesting the non-implementation represents institutional resistance rather than public opposition.',
